If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. During the game there is this dialogue:\n\n    inca: haha\n\n    Please consider what was said AND who said it, which can indicate a specific player\'s willingness to give or receive a specific resource. Reflect on how the conversation is going and the context, imagining that each utterance was written one after the other in that order. Reflect on the intentions of the players. \n    \n    How could that dialogue continue?\n\n    Very important: please respond with 1 possible continuation in this precise format: [type of utterance], [name of the player]:[utterance]\n    '}]

Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. During the game there is this dialogue:\n\n    ljaybrad123: id need two#\n\n    Please consider what was said AND who said it, which can indicate a specific player\'s willingness to give or receive a specific resource. Reflect on how the conversation is going and the context, imagining that each utterance was written one after the other in that order. Reflect on the intentions of the players. \n    \n    How could that dialogue continue?\n\n    Very important: please respond with 1 possible continuation in this precise format: [type of utterance], [name of the player]:[utterance]\n    '}]

Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players. [{'role': 'system', 'content': 'Settlers of Catan is a board game, this is a description:\n    \n    Settlers of Catan is a competitive game in which players throw 2 dice, collect resources, trade resources and try to win. Each player possesses structures adjacent to some land, and the sum of the thrown dice tell which lands will produce resources for that turn (for the players who own structures adjacent to them). There are only 5 kinds of resources: ore, wood, clay, wheat and sheep. If the sum of the rolled dice is 7, the active player moves the robber pawn to a new land and steals resources from other players who have built structures adjacent to that tile. Structures cost different combinations of resources, thus players need to trade with each other to get the resources they need.\n    \n    I will give you a dialogue from a game of Settlers, you will need to continue it with 1 possible utterance from 1 player, and 1 class.\n     \n    The admissible types of utterances, with definition are:\n\n    Offer: A proposal to trade resources between players, which isn\'t related to another offer\n    Counteroffer: A response to another player\'s offer, proposing a different trade.\n    Accept: Agreeing to an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Refusal: Declining an offer or counteroffer made by another player.\n    Other: Turns or statements that do not involve direct trading, such as discussing game mechanics or making observations about the current state of the game, including questions that aren\'t offers or counteroffers. \n    \n    Please remember: If an utterance qualifies for "Other" but also for one of the other 4 types, it should then be considered of the other type (not of the type "Other")\n    \n    A game of Settlers is being played by a group of players.
